[Oral health in the Brazilian Family Health Program: a health care model 
evaluation].

[Article in Portuguese]

Souza TM(1), Roncalli AG.

Author information:
(1)Centro de Ciências da Saúde, Universidade Federal do Rio Grande do Norte, 
Avenida das Alagoas 1689, Natal, Rio Grande do Norte, Brazil. 
tatyanaufrn@hotmail.com

The purpose of this study was to evaluate the addition of oral health teams to 
the Family Health Program in the State of Rio Grande do Norte, Brazil, by 
analyzing factors that can affect the process of changing oral health care 
models. The evaluation involved three dimensions: access, work organization, and 
planning strategies. 19 counties (municipalities) were randomly selected. The 
data collection instruments were: structured interviews with health managers and 
dentists, structured observation, and documental research. The study identified 
a lack of formal employment contracts for dentists, difficulty in referring 
patients for high-complexity procedures, and problems with the development of 
inter-sector activities, epidemiological diagnoses, and work evaluation. Most of 
the counties showed little or no improvement in oral health care. The counties 
that had improved their oral health care were the same ones with higher life 
expectancy, lower infant mortality rates, higher per capita income, and higher 
human development index (HDI). In conclusion, public policies that include 
aspects beyond the health sector are decisive for a real change in health care 
models.

