461. MMW Fortschr Med. 2007 Apr 19;149(16):27-30.

[The diagnosis is cancer--and then depression?].

[Article in German]

Nothdurfter C(1).

Author information:
(1)Klinik für Psychiatrie und Psychotherapie der LMU München. 
Caroline.Nothdurfter@med.uni-muenchen.de

Depressive disorders in patients with tumor disease are common. Owing to the 
possibility of symptom overlapping, the establishment of the diagnosis can prove 
difficult. The investigation of suicidality has a particular role to play, since 
the it may fluctuate greatly in this constellation of illnesses, and, overall, 
is very common. To date it is not clear whether psychological disorders are a 
risk factor for the development of malignant diseases. In principle, the 
spectrum of therapeutic options is virtually unlimited. However, possible 
contraindications associated with the underlying malignant disease must be 
carefully considered. All in all, establishment of the indication for 
psychopharmacological, psycho-/socio-therapeutic management should be liberal. 
In view of the reduced life expectancy of cancer victims, the highest priority 
must be given to improving the patient's quality of life.

